The idea of such a procedure was not compensation, but punishment; seli-tedress existed not so much rei, as poenae persequendae causa¹: and as there is no objective standard ol right and wrong, the measure ol the injury, and therefore ol the punishment, is the feeling ol the injured person. Traces ol this linger on in Roman Law throughout its whole history. It has been observed¹ that in settling the damages to be awarded the earliest administratore ol justice took as their guide the measure ol vengeance likely to be exacted by an aggrieved person under the circumstances ol the case’, and that this is the true explanation ol the very different penalties imposed by ancient law on offenders caught in the act, or soon aiter it, and on offenders detected alter considerable delay. Even the later Roman law permitted the husband to kill with impunity the adulterer taken flagrante delicto, and distin· guished the guilt of the thiel according as he was caught in the act or not ; the sur nocturnus was liable to the same penalty as the adul· terer: lor certain bodily injuries (Gaius iii. 223) the Mosaic law ol retaliation had its counterpart at Rome.
